subject: http://www.semanticweb.org/maxdreger/ontologies/2022/10/materials#AcetyleneBlack
object: Acetylene Black is a high-purity form of carbon black, consisting of fine particles of elemental carbon. It is commonly used as a conductive additive in lithium-ion batteries and fuel cells, due to its high surface area, electrical conductivity, and chemical stability.

subject: http://www.semanticweb.org/maxdreger/ontologies/2022/10/materials#CarbonBlack
object: Carbon black is a form of amorphous carbon, consisting of fine particles produced by the incomplete combustion of hydrocarbons. It is used as a conductive additive in lithium-ion batteries, fuel cells, and supercapacitors, due to its high surface area, electrical conductivity, and electrochemical stability.

subject: http://www.semanticweb.org/maxdreger/ontologies/2022/10/materials#Material
object: A material is any substance that has a defined chemical composition and physical properties. In the context of hydrogen technologies, materials are used in various applications such as fuel cells, electrolyzers, and hydrogen storage. Examples of materials used in these applications include metals, ceramics, polymers, and composites.

subject: http://www.semanticweb.org/maxdreger/ontologies/2022/10/materials#Matter
object: Matter is anything that has mass and takes up space. It can exist in three states: solid, liquid, or gas. In materials science, matter is studied to understand its properties and behavior, and to develop new materials with desired properties.

subject: http://www.semanticweb.org/maxdreger/ontologies/2022/10/materials#Acid
object: Acid is a chemical compound that donates hydrogen ions (H+) to a solution, lowering its pH and increasing its acidity. Acids are commonly used in hydrogen technologies as electrolytes in fuel cells and batteries to facilitate ion transport and electrochemical reactions.

subject: http://www.semanticweb.org/maxdreger/ontologies/2022/10/materials#ChemicalSubstance
object: A Chemical Substance is any material with a definite chemical composition. It can be a pure substance or a mixture of substances. In hydrogen technologies, chemical substances are used as reactants, catalysts, and electrolytes in various electrochemical processes, such as fuel cells, electrolyzers, and batteries.

subject: http://www.semanticweb.org/maxdreger/ontologies/2022/10/materials#ChemicalEntity
object: A chemical entity is any substance or compound that has a distinct molecular composition and is capable of undergoing a chemical reaction. It can be a pure substance or a mixture of substances, and can be either organic or inorganic.

subject: http://www.semanticweb.org/maxdreger/ontologies/2022/10/materials#MolecularEntity
object: A Molecular Entity is an electrically neutral group of two or more atoms held together by chemical bonds. It can be a molecule, an ion, or a radical. Molecular entities are the building blocks of all chemical substances and play a crucial role in materials science and hydrogen technologies.

subject: http://www.semanticweb.org/maxdreger/ontologies/2022/10/materials#AcidicElectrolyte
object: An acidic electrolyte is an electrolyte solution with a pH less than 7, commonly used in electrochemical devices such as batteries and fuel cells. It provides a source of ions for the electrochemical reactions to occur and facilitates the movement of ions between the electrodes.

subject: http://www.semanticweb.org/maxdreger/ontologies/2022/10/materials#AqueousElectrloyte
object: An Aqueous Electrolyte is an electrolyte solution composed of water and dissolved salts or acids. It is commonly used in electrochemical devices such as batteries, fuel cells, and supercapacitors, due to its high ionic conductivity and low cost.

subject: http://www.semanticweb.org/maxdreger/ontologies/2022/10/materials#ElectrlyteSolution
object: An electrolyte solution is a liquid or gel that contains ions and can conduct electricity. It is used in batteries, fuel cells, and other electrochemical devices to facilitate the movement of ions between the electrodes and maintain charge balance.

subject: http://www.semanticweb.org/maxdreger/ontologies/2022/10/materials#LiquidElectrolyte
object: A Liquid Electrolyte is a conductive solution used in batteries and fuel cells to facilitate the movement of ions between the electrodes. It is typically composed of a solvent and a dissolved salt or other ionic compound, and can be either aqueous or non-aqueous.

subject: http://www.semanticweb.org/maxdreger/ontologies/2022/10/materials#IonicLiquidElectrolyte
object: An Ionic Liquid Electrolyte is a type of electrolyte composed entirely of ionic liquids, which are salts that are liquid at or near room temperature. They are used in electrochemical devices such as batteries and fuel cells, offering high ionic conductivity, low volatility, and wide electrochemical stability windows.

subject: http://www.semanticweb.org/maxdreger/ontologies/2022/10/materials#Electrolyte
object: An electrolyte is a substance that conducts electricity when dissolved in a solvent, typically water. In electrochemical devices, such as batteries and fuel cells, electrolytes are used to transport ions between the electrodes, enabling the flow of electrical current.

subject: http://www.semanticweb.org/maxdreger/ontologies/2022/10/materials#SolidElectrolyte
object: A solid electrolyte is a non-liquid material that can conduct ions. It is used in batteries and fuel cells as an alternative to liquid electrolytes, offering improved safety, stability, and performance. Solid electrolytes can be made from a variety of materials, including ceramics, polymers, and composites.

subject: http://www.semanticweb.org/maxdreger/ontologies/2022/10/materials#ElectrochemicalMaterial
object: An electrochemical material is a substance that can undergo electrochemical reactions, such as oxidation and reduction, in an electrochemical cell. These materials are used in batteries, fuel cells, and other electrochemical devices to store and convert energy.

subject: http://www.semanticweb.org/maxdreger/ontologies/2022/10/materials#FunctionalMaterial
object: A functional material is a material that has specific properties or functions that make it useful for a particular application. These materials are designed to have specific physical, chemical, or biological properties that can be tailored to meet the needs of a particular application. Examples of functional materials include catalysts, semiconductors, superconductors, and biomaterials.

subject: http://www.semanticweb.org/maxdreger/ontologies/2022/10/materials#Actinium
object: Actinium is a radioactive chemical element with the symbol Ac and atomic number 89. It is a silvery-white, highly radioactive metal that is found in uranium ores. Actinium has potential applications in nuclear batteries, cancer treatment, and as a neutron source.

subject: http://www.semanticweb.org/maxdreger/ontologies/2022/10/materials#Atom
object: An atom is the basic unit of matter, consisting of a nucleus (protons and neutrons) and electrons that orbit the nucleus. Atoms are the building blocks of all chemical elements and are characterized by their atomic number, mass number, and electron configuration.

subject: http://www.semanticweb.org/maxdreger/ontologies/2022/10/materials#ActiveMaterial
object: An active material is a substance that undergoes electrochemical reactions during charge and discharge cycles in a battery or electrochemical cell. It is responsible for storing and releasing electrical energy in the device. Examples of active materials include lithium cobalt oxide, graphite, and sulfur.

subject: http://www.semanticweb.org/maxdreger/ontologies/2022/10/materials#Aerosol
object: An aerosol is a suspension of fine solid or liquid particles in a gas. In hydrogen technologies, aerosols can be used for the synthesis of nanoparticles, catalysts, and fuel cell components. Aerosol-based methods offer advantages such as high surface area, uniform particle size distribution, and precise control over particle morphology.

subject: http://www.semanticweb.org/maxdreger/ontologies/2022/10/materials#Colloid
object: A colloid is a mixture in which one substance is dispersed evenly throughout another substance. The dispersed substance is usually in the form of particles, which are larger than individual molecules but small enough to remain suspended in the mixture. Colloids have important applications in materials science, including in the synthesis of nanoparticles and in the design of advanced materials.

subject: http://www.semanticweb.org/maxdreger/ontologies/2022/10/materials#GasMixture
object: A gas mixture is a combination of two or more gases in a container, where the gases are not chemically combined. Gas mixtures are commonly used in hydrogen technologies, such as fuel cells, for various applications, including fuel storage, gas purification, and gas separation.

subject: http://www.semanticweb.org/maxdreger/ontologies/2022/10/materials#Dispersion
object: A dispersion is a mixture of two or more substances that do not dissolve in each other. The dispersed phase is made up of small particles that are suspended in the continuous phase. In materials science, dispersions are used to create composite materials with unique properties.

subject: http://www.semanticweb.org/maxdreger/ontologies/2022/10/materials#PhaseHeterogeneousMixture
object: A Phase Heterogeneous Mixture is a mixture of two or more substances that are not uniformly distributed and can be distinguished by their physical properties, such as color, density, or refractive index. Examples include suspensions, emulsions, and foams.

subject: http://www.semanticweb.org/maxdreger/ontologies/2022/10/materials#Suspension
object: A suspension is a type of heterogeneous mixture in which solid particles are dispersed in a liquid medium. The solid particles are usually insoluble in the liquid and will settle over time if left undisturbed. Suspensions are commonly used in various industrial applications, such as in the production of paints, pigments, and pharmaceuticals.

subject: http://www.semanticweb.org/maxdreger/ontologies/2022/10/materials#Gas
object: A gas is a state of matter that has no fixed shape or volume and expands to fill any available space. Gases are composed of molecules or atoms that are in constant random motion and have weak intermolecular forces.

subject: http://www.semanticweb.org/maxdreger/ontologies/2022/10/materials#Mixture
object: A mixture is a combination of two or more substances that are not chemically bonded and can be separated by physical means. Mixtures can be homogeneous or heterogeneous and can exist in any state of matter.

subject: http://www.semanticweb.org/maxdreger/ontologies/2022/10/materials#StateOfMatter
object: State of matter refers to the physical form in which matter exists, such as solid, liquid, or gas. It is an important property of materials that can affect their properties and behavior.

subject: http://www.semanticweb.org/maxdreger/ontologies/2022/10/materials#Fluid
object: A fluid is a substance that has no fixed shape and yields easily to external pressure. It can be a gas or a liquid and is used in various applications in hydrogen technologies, such as in fuel cells and electrolyzers.

subject: http://www.semanticweb.org/maxdreger/ontologies/2022/10/materials#Continuum
object: In materials science, a continuum refers to a continuous substance or material that can be modeled as a continuous field, without considering the discrete nature of its molecular or atomic structure. Continuum mechanics is a branch of mechanics that deals with the behavior of materials modeled as continua.

subject: http://www.semanticweb.org/maxdreger/ontologies/2022/10/materials#StateOfAggregation
object: State of Aggregation refers to the physical state of a material, such as solid, liquid, or gas. It is an important property that affects the behavior and properties of materials, including their reactivity, conductivity, and mechanical properties.

subject: http://www.semanticweb.org/maxdreger/ontologies/2022/10/materials#Air
object: Air is a mixture of gases, primarily nitrogen (78%) and oxygen (21%), with trace amounts of other gases such as argon, carbon dioxide, and neon. It is a common oxidant used in fuel cells and other electrochemical devices.

subject: http://www.semanticweb.org/maxdreger/ontologies/2022/10/materials#SolidSolution
object: A solid solution is a solid-state mixture of two or more substances that combine to form a single crystalline phase. In solid solutions, the atoms of the different components are randomly distributed throughout the crystal lattice, resulting in a homogeneous material with unique properties.

subject: http://www.semanticweb.org/maxdreger/ontologies/2022/10/materials#SolidMixture
object: A Solid Mixture is a combination of two or more solid materials that are physically mixed together, but not chemically bonded. Solid mixtures can be homogeneous or heterogeneous and are commonly used in materials science for tailoring properties such as strength, conductivity, and thermal stability.

subject: http://www.semanticweb.org/maxdreger/ontologies/2022/10/materials#Solution
object: An electrolyte is a substance that produces ions when dissolved in a solvent, typically a liquid. Electrolytes are used in electrochemical cells to facilitate the movement of ions between the anode and cathode, allowing for the flow of electrical current.

subject: http://www.semanticweb.org/maxdreger/ontologies/2022/10/materials#Solid
object: A crystal is a solid material whose atoms, molecules, or ions are arranged in a highly ordered, repeating pattern extending in all three spatial dimensions. Crystals exhibit unique physical and chemical properties, such as piezoelectricity, birefringence, and high thermal conductivity, making them useful in a wide range of applications, including electronics, optics, and energy storage.

subject: http://www.semanticweb.org/maxdreger/ontologies/2022/10/materials#PhaseHomogeneousMixture
object: A phase homogeneous mixture is a type of mixture where the components are uniformly distributed throughout the mixture, resulting in a single phase. The composition of the mixture is the same throughout and the properties of the mixture are uniform. Examples of phase homogeneous mixtures include solutions and alloys.

subject: http://www.semanticweb.org/maxdreger/ontologies/2022/10/materials#Alcohol
object: Alcohol is a class of organic compounds that contain a hydroxyl (-OH) functional group. It is commonly used as a solvent, fuel, and feedstock in chemical synthesis. In hydrogen technologies, alcohols such as methanol and ethanol are used as fuel in fuel cells.

subject: http://www.semanticweb.org/maxdreger/ontologies/2022/10/materials#AmphiphilSolvent
object: An amphiphilic solvent is a solvent that contains both hydrophilic (water-loving) and hydrophobic (water-fearing) regions in its molecular structure. These solvents are commonly used in materials science and electrochemistry as they can dissolve both polar and nonpolar substances. Examples of amphiphilic solvents include water-miscible organic solvents like ethanol and methanol.

subject: http://www.semanticweb.org/maxdreger/ontologies/2022/10/materials#Solvent
object: A solvent is a substance that dissolves a solute to form a solution. In hydrogen technologies, solvents are used in various processes such as electrolyte preparation, catalyst synthesis, and fuel cell fabrication. Common solvents include water, alcohols, and organic solvents such as dimethyl sulfoxide (DMSO) and N-methyl-2-pyrrolidone (NMP).

subject: http://www.semanticweb.org/maxdreger/ontologies/2022/10/materials#AlicyclicHeterocylclicOrganicMolecules
object: Alicyclic and Heterocyclic Organic Molecules are organic compounds that contain cyclic structures, such as rings, and may also contain heteroatoms, such as nitrogen, oxygen, or sulfur. These molecules have diverse applications in materials science, including as solvents, monomers, and ligands for catalysis and coordination chemistry.

subject: http://www.semanticweb.org/maxdreger/ontologies/2022/10/materials#HeteroCyclicOrganicMolecules
object: Heterocyclic organic molecules are organic compounds that contain at least one heteroatom (an atom other than carbon) in their ring structure. They have diverse applications in materials science, including as dyes, pharmaceuticals, and organic semiconductors.

subject: http://www.semanticweb.org/maxdreger/ontologies/2022/10/materials#AromaticHeterocyclicOrganicMolecules
object: Aromatic heterocyclic organic molecules are organic compounds that contain a ring structure made up of carbon atoms and at least one heteroatom (such as nitrogen, oxygen, or sulfur) in the ring. These molecules have unique electronic properties that make them useful in a variety of applications, including as dyes, pharmaceuticals, and organic semiconductors.

subject: http://www.semanticweb.org/maxdreger/ontologies/2022/10/materials#CyclicOrganicMolecules
object: Cyclic organic molecules are organic compounds that contain one or more closed rings of atoms in their structure. They have a wide range of applications in materials science, including as building blocks for polymers, pharmaceuticals, and agrochemicals.

subject: http://www.semanticweb.org/maxdreger/ontologies/2022/10/materials#HomocyclicOrganicMolecules
object: Homocyclic Organic Molecules are organic compounds that contain only carbon atoms in their rings. These molecules are also known as carbocyclic compounds and are classified based on the number of carbon atoms in their rings. They have various applications in organic synthesis, pharmaceuticals, and materials science.

subject: http://www.semanticweb.org/maxdreger/ontologies/2022/10/materials#OrganicMolceule
object: A cyclic organic molecule is a type of organic molecule that contains a closed ring of atoms in its structure. These molecules have a wide range of applications in materials science, including as building blocks for polymers, pharmaceuticals, and agrochemicals.

subject: http://www.semanticweb.org/maxdreger/ontologies/2022/10/materials#OpenChainOrganicMolecules
object: Open-chain organic molecules, also known as acyclic or aliphatic molecules, are organic compounds that do not contain a cyclic structure. They are characterized by a linear or branched chain of carbon atoms, and can include functional groups such as alkanes, alkenes, and alkynes. Open-chain organic molecules have a wide range of applications in organic chemistry, materials science, and biochemistry.

subject: http://www.semanticweb.org/maxdreger/ontologies/2022/10/materials#OrganicCompound
object: An organic compound is a type of chemical compound that contains carbon atoms bonded to hydrogen atoms, along with other elements such as oxygen, nitrogen, sulfur, and halogens. Organic compounds are widely used in hydrogen technologies, including as solvents, electrolytes, and catalysts.

subject: http://www.semanticweb.org/maxdreger/ontologies/2022/10/materials#ChemicalCompound
object: A chemical compound is a substance composed of two or more elements chemically bonded together in a fixed ratio. Chemical compounds have unique physical and chemical properties that differ from their constituent elements.

subject: http://www.semanticweb.org/maxdreger/ontologies/2022/10/materials#AlicyclicHomocylclicOrganicMolecules
object: Alicyclic homocyclic organic molecules are cyclic organic compounds that contain only carbon atoms in the ring structure. They are characterized by having a closed ring of atoms with no double or triple bonds and are commonly used as solvents, monomers, and intermediates in organic synthesis.

subject: http://www.semanticweb.org/maxdreger/ontologies/2022/10/materials#AromaticAlicyclicOrganicMolecules
object: Aromatic Alicyclic Organic Molecules are organic compounds that contain both aromatic and alicyclic (non-aromatic cyclic) structural elements. These molecules have unique properties, such as high thermal stability, rigidity, and resistance to oxidation, making them useful in various applications, including as solvents, monomers, and pharmaceuticals.

subject: http://www.semanticweb.org/maxdreger/ontologies/2022/10/materials#AlkalineElectrolyte
object: An Alkaline Electrolyte is a type of electrolyte used in alkaline fuel cells, consisting of a solution of potassium hydroxide (KOH) or sodium hydroxide (NaOH) in water. Alkaline electrolytes offer high ionic conductivity and are less prone to carbonation than acidic electrolytes.

subject: http://www.semanticweb.org/maxdreger/ontologies/2022/10/materials#Alkanes
object: Alkanes are a family of organic compounds consisting of carbon and hydrogen atoms, with only single covalent bonds between the atoms. They are commonly used as fuels and solvents in hydrogen technologies, and can be converted into hydrogen gas through steam reforming or other processes.

subject: http://www.semanticweb.org/maxdreger/ontologies/2022/10/materials#Alkenes
object: Alkenes are unsaturated hydrocarbons that contain at least one carbon-carbon double bond. They are important in hydrogen technologies as they can be used as feedstocks for the production of hydrogen gas through steam methane reforming or partial oxidation.

subject: http://www.semanticweb.org/maxdreger/ontologies/2022/10/materials#Alkynes
object: Alkynes are unsaturated hydrocarbons that contain a carbon-carbon triple bond. They are used in organic synthesis, as starting materials for the production of polymers, and as fuels.

subject: http://www.semanticweb.org/maxdreger/ontologies/2022/10/materials#Aluminium
object: Aluminum is a lightweight, corrosion-resistant metal with good electrical conductivity. It is commonly used in hydrogen technologies as a component of fuel cell bipolar plates, hydrogen storage tanks, and electrolysis electrodes.

subject: http://www.semanticweb.org/maxdreger/ontologies/2022/10/materials#Americium
object: Americium is a radioactive, silvery-white metal that is part of the actinide series. It is primarily used in nuclear research and as a source of ionizing radiation for industrial gauges and smoke detectors. Americium has potential applications in nuclear batteries and spacecraft power systems.

subject: http://www.semanticweb.org/maxdreger/ontologies/2022/10/materials#Anion
object: An anion is a negatively charged ion that migrates to the anode (positive electrode) in an electrolytic cell. It is an atom or molecule that has gained one or more electrons, resulting in a net negative charge.

subject: http://www.semanticweb.org/maxdreger/ontologies/2022/10/materials#Ion
object: An ion is an atom or molecule that has an unequal number of protons and electrons, resulting in a net electrical charge. Ions can be positively charged (called cations) or negatively charged (called anions) and play important roles in electrochemical reactions.

subject: http://www.semanticweb.org/maxdreger/ontologies/2022/10/materials#AnisotropicMaterial
object: An Anisotropic Material is a material that exhibits different properties in different directions. It has physical or mechanical properties that vary with the direction of measurement. Anisotropic materials are commonly used in fuel cell and battery components, such as electrodes and membranes, to optimize their performance in specific directions.

subject: http://www.semanticweb.org/maxdreger/ontologies/2022/10/materials#Anolyte
object: An anolyte is an electrolyte solution that is located at the anode of an electrochemical cell. It is responsible for providing ions to the anode and facilitating the electrochemical reactions that occur at the anode during cell operation.

subject: http://www.semanticweb.org/maxdreger/ontologies/2022/10/materials#ElectrolyteSolution
object: An electrolyte solution is a liquid or gel containing ions that conducts electricity and is used in batteries, fuel cells, and other electrochemical devices. It facilitates the movement of ions between the electrodes, allowing the electrochemical reactions to occur.

subject: http://www.semanticweb.org/maxdreger/ontologies/2022/10/materials#LiquidSolution
object: A liquid solution is a homogeneous mixture of two or more substances in which the molecules or atoms of the substances are evenly distributed. The solvent is the substance that dissolves the solute(s) to form the solution. Liquid solutions are commonly used in chemical reactions, separations, and as solvents for other substances.

subject: http://www.semanticweb.org/maxdreger/ontologies/2022/10/materials#Liquid
object: A liquid is a state of matter that has a definite volume but no fixed shape. It can flow and take the shape of its container. Liquids are commonly used as solvents, electrolytes, and reactants in chemical reactions.

subject: http://www.semanticweb.org/maxdreger/ontologies/2022/10/materials#Antimony
object: Antimony is a chemical element with the symbol Sb and atomic number 51. It is a lustrous, gray metalloid that is commonly used as a flame retardant, alloyed with lead for batteries, and used in the production of semiconductors.

subject: http://www.semanticweb.org/maxdreger/ontologies/2022/10/materials#AqueousElectrolyte
object: An aqueous electrolyte is a solution containing ions that conducts electricity and is composed of water as the solvent. It is commonly used in electrochemical devices such as batteries, fuel cells, and supercapacitors.

subject: http://www.semanticweb.org/maxdreger/ontologies/2022/10/materials#AqueousSolution
object: An aqueous solution is a solution in which the solvent is water. It is commonly used in electrochemistry as an electrolyte solution, where it facilitates the movement of ions between the electrodes. Aqueous solutions are also used in a wide range of chemical reactions and industrial processes.

subject: http://www.semanticweb.org/maxdreger/ontologies/2022/10/materials#AqueousMolecule
object: An aqueous molecule is a molecule that is dissolved in water, forming an aqueous solution. These molecules can be organic or inorganic and are commonly used in chemical reactions and biological processes.

subject: http://www.semanticweb.org/maxdreger/ontologies/2022/10/materials#DissolvedMolecule
object: A dissolved molecule is a molecule that is uniformly dispersed in a solvent to form a homogeneous solution. The dissolved molecule can be a solute, which is the substance being dissolved, or a solvent, which is the substance doing the dissolving. Dissolved molecules play a critical role in many chemical and biological processes, including solubility, transport, and reaction kinetics.

subject: http://www.semanticweb.org/maxdreger/ontologies/2022/10/materials#NonAqeousMolecule
object: A non-aqueous molecule is a molecule that is not soluble in water or does not contain water as a solvent. Non-aqueous solvents are commonly used in electrochemical applications, such as in lithium-ion batteries and supercapacitors, due to their high chemical stability and wide electrochemical window.

subject: http://www.semanticweb.org/maxdreger/ontologies/2022/10/materials#MolecularEntityInStateOfAggregation
object: A Molecular Entity in State of Aggregation refers to a chemical species that is composed of two or more molecules held together by intermolecular forces. Examples include dimers, trimers, and other oligomers. These species can have unique properties and reactivity compared to their individual molecular components.

subject: http://www.semanticweb.org/maxdreger/ontologies/2022/10/materials#Aquivion
object: Aquivion is a perfluorosulfonic acid (PFSA) ionomer membrane used in proton exchange membrane (PEM) fuel cells. It offers high proton conductivity, chemical stability, and mechanical durability, making it a popular choice for fuel cell applications.

subject: http://www.semanticweb.org/maxdreger/ontologies/2022/10/materials#Ionomer
object: Ionomers are a class of materials that contain ionic groups, which can conduct ions. They are used in fuel cells and other electrochemical devices as membranes or coatings to facilitate ion transport. Aquivion is a type of ionomer that is based on perfluorosulfonic acid and is known for its high proton conductivity and chemical stability.

subject: http://www.semanticweb.org/maxdreger/ontologies/2022/6/FCFabChar#Polymer
object: A polymer is a large molecule composed of repeating subunits called monomers. Polymers have a wide range of applications in hydrogen technologies, including as electrolyte membranes, ionomers, and electrode binders in fuel cells and batteries.

subject: http://www.semanticweb.org/maxdreger/ontologies/2022/10/materials#AquivionD72-25BS
object: Aquivion D72-25BS is a perfluorosulfonic acid ionomer membrane used in proton exchange membrane fuel cells. It has a high proton conductivity, good chemical stability, and high mechanical strength, making it suitable for use in harsh environments.

subject: http://www.semanticweb.org/maxdreger/ontologies/2022/10/materials#AquivionD79-25BS
object: Aquivion D79-25BS is a perfluorosulfonic acid ionomer membrane used in proton exchange membrane fuel cells. It has a high ion exchange capacity and good mechanical properties, making it suitable for use in high-temperature and low-humidity environments.

subject: http://www.semanticweb.org/maxdreger/ontologies/2022/10/materials#AquivionD98-25BS
object: Aquivion D98-25BS is a perfluorosulfonic acid ionomer membrane used in proton exchange membrane fuel cells. It has a high ion exchange capacity and excellent proton conductivity, making it suitable for use in high-temperature fuel cells.

subject: http://www.semanticweb.org/maxdreger/ontologies/2022/10/materials#AquivionSO3H-Form
object: Aquivion SO3H-Form is a perfluorosulfonic acid ionomer used as a proton exchange membrane in fuel cells. It has a high proton conductivity, good chemical stability, and high thermal stability, making it suitable for use in high-temperature fuel cells.

subject: http://www.semanticweb.org/maxdreger/ontologies/2022/10/materials#Argon
object: Argon is a chemical element with the symbol Ar and atomic number 18. It is a noble gas and is the third-most abundant gas in the Earth's atmosphere. Argon is used in various applications, including welding, lighting, and as a protective gas in the production of titanium and other reactive elements.

subject: http://www.semanticweb.org/maxdreger/ontologies/2022/10/materials#AromaticHeterocyclicOrganicAminesMolecules
object: Aromatic Heterocyclic Organic Amines Molecules are organic compounds that contain both an amine group and an aromatic heterocyclic ring in their structure. They are used in various applications such as pharmaceuticals, agrochemicals, and dyes. These molecules exhibit unique electronic and steric properties, making them useful in a wide range of chemical reactions.

subject: http://www.semanticweb.org/maxdreger/ontologies/2022/10/materials#Arsenic
object: Arsenic is a chemical element with the symbol As and atomic number 33. It is a metalloid commonly used in the semiconductor industry and as a doping agent in some electronic devices. Arsenic and its compounds are also used in wood preservatives, pesticides, and herbicides, but are highly toxic and carcinogenic.

subject: http://www.semanticweb.org/maxdreger/ontologies/2022/10/materials#Astatine
object: Astatine is a rare and highly radioactive element with the symbol At and atomic number 85. It is a member of the halogen family and is the heaviest known halogen. Astatine has no stable isotopes and is typically produced by bombarding bismuth with alpha particles. It has potential applications in targeted alpha-particle therapy for cancer treatment.

subject: http://www.semanticweb.org/maxdreger/ontologies/2022/10/materials#Barium
object: Barium is a chemical element with the symbol Ba and atomic number 56. It is a soft, silvery-white metal that belongs to the alkaline earth metals. Barium has a variety of applications, including in the production of vacuum tubes, fluorescent lamps, and fireworks.

subject: http://www.semanticweb.org/maxdreger/ontologies/2022/10/materials#Base
object: A base is a substance that can accept hydrogen ions (protons) or donate hydroxide ions in a chemical reaction. In electrochemistry, bases are used as electrolytes in alkaline batteries and fuel cells, where they facilitate the flow of ions between the electrodes.

subject: http://www.semanticweb.org/maxdreger/ontologies/2022/10/materials#Berkelium
object: Berkelium is a synthetic, radioactive element with the symbol Bk and atomic number 97. It is a member of the actinide series and is named after the city of Berkeley, California, where it was first synthesized. Berkelium has no commercial applications but is used in scientific research, particularly in the study of nuclear properties and as a target material for the synthesis of heavier elements.

subject: http://www.semanticweb.org/maxdreger/ontologies/2022/10/materials#Beryllium
object: Beryllium is a lightweight, strong, and brittle metal that is commonly used as a structural material in aerospace, defense, and nuclear industries. It is also used as a neutron reflector in nuclear reactors and in X-ray windows due to its low atomic number and high transparency to X-rays.

subject: http://www.semanticweb.org/maxdreger/ontologies/2022/10/materials#BinaryCarbonSupportedPlatinumCatalyst
object: A Binary Carbon Supported Platinum Catalyst is a type of catalyst used in fuel cells, consisting of platinum nanoparticles supported on a carbon black substrate. It is used as a cathode catalyst in proton exchange membrane fuel cells, offering high activity, stability, and durability.

subject: http://www.semanticweb.org/maxdreger/ontologies/2022/10/materials#PlatinumCatalyst
object: A Platinum Catalyst is a material that accelerates chemical reactions by providing an alternative pathway with lower activation energy. It is commonly used in fuel cells, electrolyzers, and other electrochemical devices to facilitate the conversion of reactants into products. Platinum is a popular catalyst material due to its high activity, stability, and resistance to corrosion.

subject: http://www.semanticweb.org/maxdreger/ontologies/2022/10/materials#SingleMetalCatalyst
object: A Single Metal Catalyst is a type of catalyst that consists of only one type of metal, such as platinum, palladium, or iridium. It is used in various chemical reactions, including hydrogenation, oxidation, and reduction, to increase the rate of the reaction and improve its efficiency.

subject: http://www.semanticweb.org/maxdreger/ontologies/2022/10/materials#ElectroCatalyst
object: An electrocatalyst is a material that increases the rate of an electrochemical reaction by lowering the activation energy required for the reaction to occur. It is used in electrochemical devices such as fuel cells, batteries, and electrolyzers to facilitate the conversion of chemical energy into electrical energy and vice versa.

subject: http://www.semanticweb.org/maxdreger/ontologies/2022/10/materials#Catalyst
object: A catalyst is a substance that increases the rate of a chemical reaction without undergoing any permanent chemical change itself. In hydrogen technologies, catalysts are used to facilitate the electrochemical reactions that convert chemical energy into electrical energy in fuel cells and electrolyzers.

subject: http://www.semanticweb.org/maxdreger/ontologies/2022/10/materials#BinaryCatalyst
object: A binary catalyst is a type of catalyst composed of two different elements or compounds. In hydrogen technologies, binary catalysts are commonly used in fuel cells to promote the electrochemical reactions that convert hydrogen and oxygen into water and electricity. Examples of binary catalysts include platinum-ruthenium, platinum-tin, and platinum-cobalt.

subject: http://www.semanticweb.org/maxdreger/ontologies/2022/10/materials#BinaryMaterial
object: A Binary Material is a material composed of two different chemical elements or compounds. In the context of hydrogen technologies, binary materials are often used as catalysts or electrode materials in fuel cells and electrolyzers.

subject: http://www.semanticweb.org/maxdreger/ontologies/2022/10/materials#Bismuth
object: Bismuth is a chemical element with the symbol Bi and atomic number 83. It is a dense, silvery-white metal with a pinkish tint. Bismuth is commonly used in cosmetics, alloys, and pharmaceuticals. It is also used as a substitute for lead in some applications due to its low toxicity.

subject: http://www.semanticweb.org/maxdreger/ontologies/2022/10/materials#Bohrium
object: Bohrium is a synthetic chemical element with the symbol Bh and atomic number 107. It is a highly radioactive metal and belongs to the group of transuranium elements. It is named after Danish physicist Niels Bohr.

subject: http://www.semanticweb.org/maxdreger/ontologies/2022/10/materials#Boron
object: Boron is a chemical element with the symbol B and atomic number 5. It is a metalloid and is commonly used in the form of borates, which are used in the production of glass, ceramics, and detergents. Boron is also used as a dopant in semiconductors and as a neutron absorber in nuclear reactors.

subject: http://www.semanticweb.org/maxdreger/ontologies/2022/10/materials#Bromine
object: Bromine is a halogen element with the symbol Br and atomic number 35. It is a reddish-brown liquid at room temperature and is the only nonmetallic element that is liquid under normal conditions. Bromine is used in the production of flame retardants, water purification, and pharmaceuticals.

subject: http://www.semanticweb.org/maxdreger/ontologies/2022/10/materials#Cadmium
object: Cadmium is a soft, bluish-white metal that is commonly used in batteries, pigments, and coatings. It is also used in nuclear reactors as a neutron absorber and in solar cells as a semiconductor material.

subject: http://www.semanticweb.org/maxdreger/ontologies/2022/10/materials#Calcium
object: Calcium is a chemical element with the symbol Ca and atomic number 20. It is a soft, silvery-white metal that belongs to the alkaline earth metals. Calcium is an important element in the production of alloys, as a reducing agent in the extraction of other metals, and in the production of cement and mortar.

subject: http://www.semanticweb.org/maxdreger/ontologies/2022/10/materials#Californium
object: Californium is a radioactive, synthetic element with the symbol Cf and atomic number 98. It is a highly reactive and rare element, primarily used in scientific research and nuclear reactors.

subject: http://www.semanticweb.org/maxdreger/ontologies/2022/10/materials#CarbonSupportedPlatinumCatalyst
object: A Carbon-Supported Platinum Catalyst is a type of electrocatalyst used in fuel cells, consisting of platinum nanoparticles supported on a carbon substrate. It is used to facilitate the oxygen reduction reaction (ORR) at the cathode in fuel cells, improving their efficiency and performance.

subject: http://www.semanticweb.org/maxdreger/ontologies/2022/10/materials#CatalystInk
object: A Catalyst Ink is a suspension of catalyst particles in a solvent, used for the deposition of catalyst layers onto electrode surfaces in fuel cells and other electrochemical devices. The ink is typically composed of a catalyst, a solvent, and a binder, and is applied to the electrode surface using various deposition techniques such as spraying, painting, or screen printing.

subject: http://www.semanticweb.org/maxdreger/ontologies/2022/10/materials#Catholyte
object: A catholyte is an electrolyte solution that is used in redox flow batteries as the cathode half-cell. It is typically composed of a metal salt dissolved in a solvent and is responsible for facilitating the electrochemical reactions that occur at the cathode during battery operation.

subject: http://www.semanticweb.org/maxdreger/ontologies/2022/10/materials#Cation
object: A cation is an ion with a positive charge, which is formed when an atom loses one or more electrons. In electrochemistry, cations are attracted to the cathode, where they can gain electrons and be reduced.

subject: http://www.semanticweb.org/maxdreger/ontologies/2022/10/materials#Ceramic
object: Ceramic is a non-metallic, inorganic solid material that is typically made from a combination of metallic and non-metallic elements. Ceramics are used in a wide range of applications, including fuel cells, batteries, and catalysis, due to their high-temperature stability, chemical resistance, and electrical insulation properties.

subject: http://www.semanticweb.org/maxdreger/ontologies/2022/10/materials#Cerium
object: Cerium is a chemical element with the symbol Ce and atomic number 58. It is a soft, silvery, ductile metal that easily oxidizes in air. Cerium is widely used in catalytic converters, glass polishing, and as a component of mischmetal, a pyrophoric alloy used in lighter flints.

subject: http://www.semanticweb.org/maxdreger/ontologies/2022/10/materials#Cesium
object: Cesium is a highly reactive alkali metal with atomic number 55. It is used in various applications such as atomic clocks, photoelectric cells, and catalysts. Cesium-based catalysts are used in organic synthesis reactions, and as a promoter for other catalysts.

subject: http://www.semanticweb.org/maxdreger/ontologies/2022/10/materials#ChannelBlack
object: Channel Black is a form of carbon black that is used as a conductive additive in lithium-ion batteries. It is a highly porous material with a large surface area, which enhances the electrical conductivity and mechanical strength of the battery electrodes.

subject: http://www.semanticweb.org/maxdreger/ontologies/2022/10/materials#ChemicalReactionProduct
object: A Chemical Reaction Product is a substance formed as a result of a chemical reaction. It can be a solid, liquid, or gas and can have different properties than the reactants. In hydrogen technologies, chemical reaction products can include water, oxygen, and carbon dioxide.

subject: http://www.semanticweb.org/maxdreger/ontologies/2022/10/materials#ChemicalReationReactant
object: A chemical reaction reactant is a substance that participates in a chemical reaction and undergoes a chemical change. It is typically consumed during the reaction and is transformed into one or more products.

subject: http://www.semanticweb.org/maxdreger/ontologies/2022/10/materials#Chlorine
object: Chlorine is a highly reactive, yellow-green gas that belongs to the halogen group of elements. It is widely used in the chemical industry for the production of a variety of chemicals, including solvents, pesticides, and plastics. Chlorine is also used as a disinfectant in water treatment and swimming pools.

subject: http://www.semanticweb.org/maxdreger/ontologies/2022/10/materials#Chromium
object: Chromium is a chemical element with the symbol Cr and atomic number 24. It is a hard, lustrous, steel-gray metal that is highly resistant to corrosion and tarnishing. Chromium is widely used in the production of stainless steel, as well as in the aerospace, automotive, and electronics industries.

subject: http://www.semanticweb.org/maxdreger/ontologies/2022/10/materials#CoatingSubstrate
object: A coating substrate is a material onto which a coating is applied. The substrate can be a metal, ceramic, or polymer and is chosen based on the desired properties of the coating and the application requirements.

subject: http://www.semanticweb.org/maxdreger/ontologies/2022/10/materials#Cobalt
object: Cobalt is a transition metal with the symbol Co and atomic number 27. It is commonly used in the production of rechargeable batteries, particularly in the cathode material of lithium-ion batteries. Cobalt-based alloys are also used in the manufacture of gas turbines, jet engines, and other high-performance machinery.
